00:00:21.900 --> 00:00:24.600
SE BAEK OH: So today's class,
we are going to talk about--

00:00:24.600 --> 00:00:25.670
called coherence.

00:00:25.670 --> 00:00:31.310
And basically Fourier system
with incoherent imaging.

00:00:31.310 --> 00:00:34.490
So particularly, this
topic is very important

00:00:34.490 --> 00:00:37.520
if you want to take our optics
course because We're dealing

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:39.125
with coherence and incoherence.

00:00:43.070 --> 00:00:45.590
So far, we have dealt
with the Fourier system

00:00:45.590 --> 00:00:48.350
with a coherent illumination.

00:00:48.350 --> 00:00:52.340
Basically, laser light
from a point source--

00:00:52.340 --> 00:00:53.180
I mean, pinhole.

00:00:53.180 --> 00:00:59.360
So the coherent plane waves
illuminating the Fourier

00:00:59.360 --> 00:01:04.480
system, and the frequency
content appears at the plane.

00:01:04.480 --> 00:01:06.830
And you can put the
[INAUDIBLE] mask

00:01:06.830 --> 00:01:10.910
to play with the
spatial filtering,

00:01:10.910 --> 00:01:14.880
and you're going to get some
image at the alpha plane.

00:01:14.880 --> 00:01:19.730
But in everyday life, if
you use your digital camera,

00:01:19.730 --> 00:01:23.390
you're not using the
really laser illumination.

00:01:23.390 --> 00:01:28.190
You mostly use this ambient
light, or if it's too dark,

00:01:28.190 --> 00:01:32.460
then you're going to
use the flashlight.

00:01:32.460 --> 00:01:36.720
So today, we are going to talk
about more realistic case.

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:38.600
We use the incoherent light.

00:01:38.600 --> 00:01:42.290
By the way, the difference
between coherent and incoherent

00:01:42.290 --> 00:01:45.530
is basically, you can
make the interference

00:01:45.530 --> 00:01:47.060
with the coherent light.

00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:49.130
So if you're not
make interference--

00:01:49.130 --> 00:01:52.190
you're using laser,
but in most case,

00:01:52.190 --> 00:01:53.690
like this white
light source, you're

00:01:53.690 --> 00:01:55.910
not going to see interference.

00:01:55.910 --> 00:02:00.590
So we're going to first
define what coherence is.

00:02:00.590 --> 00:02:02.210
And actually,
there are two kinds

00:02:02.210 --> 00:02:06.230
of coherence, temporal
coherence and spatial coherence.

00:02:06.230 --> 00:02:08.570
And the rest of the topic
is pretty straightforward.

00:02:08.570 --> 00:02:14.750
We will define incoherent point
spread function and its Fourier

00:02:14.750 --> 00:02:17.300
transform which is
optical transfer function

00:02:17.300 --> 00:02:19.370
and modulation transfer
function, which

00:02:19.370 --> 00:02:22.850
is modulus of OTF.

00:02:22.850 --> 00:02:25.760
And we're going to
see what MTF means.

00:02:25.760 --> 00:02:28.250
And we want to
compare the difference

00:02:28.250 --> 00:02:32.861
between spatially coherent
and incoherent images.

00:02:38.660 --> 00:02:40.400
So as I just described,
the coherence

00:02:40.400 --> 00:02:45.090
is basically ability
to make interference.

00:02:45.090 --> 00:02:47.750
So if you have incoherent light,
you cannot make interference.

00:02:47.750 --> 00:02:49.850
And if you have
coherent light, then you

00:02:49.850 --> 00:02:51.530
can make the interference.

00:02:51.530 --> 00:02:55.663
And I'm going to describe it
later, but mathematically--

00:02:55.663 --> 00:02:57.080
actually, the
coherence is nothing

00:02:57.080 --> 00:03:03.050
but the correlation of wave at
two time space points, which

00:03:03.050 --> 00:03:08.090
means we have some light, and
you just sample two points.

00:03:08.090 --> 00:03:11.750
It could be different time
points, but you combine them.

00:03:11.750 --> 00:03:14.450
And if you see interference,
then you can say it's coherent.

00:03:14.450 --> 00:03:16.270
But if you don't
see interference,

00:03:16.270 --> 00:03:19.160
then it is incoherent.

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:21.930
So first, let me
describe what's going

00:03:21.930 --> 00:03:25.100
to happen if I use the
incoherent light in Michelson

00:03:25.100 --> 00:03:25.730
interferometer.

00:03:25.730 --> 00:03:28.850
So here, we have the
Michelson interferometer.

00:03:28.850 --> 00:03:31.740
So from the point
source, the light--

00:03:31.740 --> 00:03:38.240
oops-- is coming in this
direction, this direction.

00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:41.450
And at the beam splitter,
half of the light

00:03:41.450 --> 00:03:44.090
just transmit the beam
splitter, but the other half

00:03:44.090 --> 00:03:45.680
is reflected.

00:03:45.680 --> 00:03:48.470
So this path gets reflected
again at the mirror,

00:03:48.470 --> 00:03:50.090
and passed through
the beam splitter,

00:03:50.090 --> 00:03:52.010
and arrives at the detector.

00:03:52.010 --> 00:03:55.815
And the other path is
reflected again, and reflected

00:03:55.815 --> 00:03:56.690
at the beam splitter.

00:03:56.690 --> 00:03:58.850
And again you get--

00:03:58.850 --> 00:04:01.530
I mean, it arrives
at the detector.

00:04:04.490 --> 00:04:10.055
So let's just suppose that we
have the laser source here.

00:04:10.055 --> 00:04:11.930
Then what you're going
to see at the detector

00:04:11.930 --> 00:04:15.940
is a nice sinusoidal pattern
if I move one of the mirror.

00:04:15.940 --> 00:04:23.990
Because I can tune the optical
path length that light travels.

00:04:23.990 --> 00:04:27.080
And if the distance
match, then I

00:04:27.080 --> 00:04:28.550
get the constructive
interference.

00:04:28.550 --> 00:04:33.590
And if the phase delay pi, then
I get disruptive interference.

00:04:33.590 --> 00:04:35.690
So as I move the
one with the mirror,

00:04:35.690 --> 00:04:39.015
I get nice sinusoidal pattern
with the full contrast.

00:04:43.410 --> 00:04:48.400
And next, let's suppose
instead of the laser,

00:04:48.400 --> 00:04:51.350
I have incoherent
source, which means--

00:04:51.350 --> 00:04:54.880
so the horizontal axis is
time, and the vertical axis

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:56.065
is amplitude.

00:04:56.065 --> 00:05:00.100
But the phase or amplitude
is varying randomly.

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:10.510
So over time, the amplitudes
are varying randomly.

00:05:10.510 --> 00:05:15.730
And even though it's
random, this wave train

00:05:15.730 --> 00:05:18.730
will travel through
the interferometer.

00:05:18.730 --> 00:05:28.570
So in this path, the
optical path length

00:05:28.570 --> 00:05:30.380
is actually constant, which is--

00:05:30.380 --> 00:05:33.680
I mean, these paths,
they're common in two path.

00:05:33.680 --> 00:05:37.510
So constants plus 2d1
over c, which is time--

00:05:37.510 --> 00:05:39.110
speed of light.

00:05:39.110 --> 00:05:43.270
And in the second
path, I have the same--

00:05:43.270 --> 00:05:44.780
this wave train also travels.

00:05:44.780 --> 00:05:49.530
But due to the difference
between d1 and d2,

00:05:49.530 --> 00:05:51.550
at the detector,
essentially, I'm

00:05:51.550 --> 00:05:53.480
going to sample a
different time point.

00:05:53.480 --> 00:05:57.460
So even though it's
random, I basically

00:05:57.460 --> 00:06:01.210
choose two time
points here and here,

00:06:01.210 --> 00:06:04.600
and combine them
at the detector.

00:06:04.600 --> 00:06:10.720
So if the d1 and d2 are
same, then basically,

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:13.340
identical two waves
are coming together,

00:06:13.340 --> 00:06:16.150
so I always get
constructive interference.

00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:19.300
But what if d1 and
d2 are not same?

00:06:19.300 --> 00:06:23.860
And then basically, they
get different phase shift.

00:06:23.860 --> 00:06:28.720
And since it's random,
they kind of average out.

00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:30.830
So d1 and d2 are getting bigger.

00:06:30.830 --> 00:06:34.930
Then basically, the
degree of correlation

00:06:34.930 --> 00:06:39.700
is getting decreased, which
means at the detector,

00:06:39.700 --> 00:06:43.780
the contrast will
also get decreased.

00:06:43.780 --> 00:06:47.830
So if I plot the intensity
at the detector with respect

00:06:47.830 --> 00:06:52.110
to d2 minus d1, which is the
distance difference of two

00:06:52.110 --> 00:06:57.010
arms, then the intensity
is going to be like this.

00:06:57.010 --> 00:07:02.800
So remember that if I have the
laser at point source, then

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:07.180
I will get the sinusoidal
pattern with the full contrast.

00:07:07.180 --> 00:07:11.860
But since now I have the
randomly varying source,

00:07:11.860 --> 00:07:14.060
this envelop is getting
attenuated like this.

00:07:14.060 --> 00:07:18.490
So if I have the rapid
decay curve, which means

00:07:18.490 --> 00:07:20.570
I have more incoherent light.

00:07:20.570 --> 00:07:23.390
And if I have the
slowly decaying envelop,

00:07:23.390 --> 00:07:24.550
then it's more coherent.

00:07:29.490 --> 00:07:35.290
And there is another
kind of coherence

00:07:35.290 --> 00:07:36.760
which is spatial coherence.

00:07:36.760 --> 00:07:38.510
So basically, the
concept is the same,

00:07:38.510 --> 00:07:43.240
but we only define the
correlation in space domain.

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:46.060
So now I have the Young
interferometer, which

00:07:46.060 --> 00:07:48.390
I have two pinholes, x1 and x2.

00:07:48.390 --> 00:07:51.850
And I put a detector at the
center of the two pinholes.

00:07:51.850 --> 00:07:56.350
So from this pinhole, we see--

00:07:56.350 --> 00:07:59.830
I mean, the spherical wave
is going to be emanating,

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:05.050
but since it is at the center,
these paths are exactly same.

00:08:05.050 --> 00:08:08.770
And first, let's suppose
we have laser illumination.

00:08:08.770 --> 00:08:11.650
So I have the plane
wave coming in.

00:08:11.650 --> 00:08:15.010
Then this spherical wave will
make the Young's interference.

00:08:15.010 --> 00:08:18.640
So I'm going to have
the sinusoidal pattern

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:21.250
with the full contrast
at this plane,

00:08:21.250 --> 00:08:23.530
but I'm just seeing
at one point.

00:08:23.530 --> 00:08:32.059
And again, if I have the
randomly varying wave here--

00:08:32.059 --> 00:08:36.280
so in this case, this
horizontal axis amplitude

00:08:36.280 --> 00:08:39.820
and vertical axis is
space instead of time.

00:08:39.820 --> 00:08:46.000
So this amplitude and phase are
randomly varying over space.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:49.450
Since I have two
pinholes, so I essentially

00:08:49.450 --> 00:08:54.490
sample at two points here
and there, and combine them.

00:08:58.520 --> 00:09:02.140
So again, if these two
pinholes are very close,

00:09:02.140 --> 00:09:04.990
then these sampling points
are also very close.

00:09:04.990 --> 00:09:10.390
So the amplitude and phase
are more likely similar.

00:09:10.390 --> 00:09:12.550
[INAUDIBLE]

00:09:12.550 --> 00:09:17.620
But if I move these two pinholes
in the upward and downward

00:09:17.620 --> 00:09:20.760
like this, then the spacing
between two pinholes

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:22.660
are getting bigger,
and basically, I

00:09:22.660 --> 00:09:25.840
lose the correlation,
which means

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:29.780
the spatial coherence is getting
attenuated-- getting smaller.

00:09:29.780 --> 00:09:33.490
So again, if I
plot the intensity

00:09:33.490 --> 00:09:37.900
at the detector with respect
to x2 minus x1, which

00:09:37.900 --> 00:09:41.140
is the spacing
between two pinholes,

00:09:41.140 --> 00:09:46.258
then intensity
varying like this.

00:09:46.258 --> 00:09:47.800
Again, remember, if
I have the laser,

00:09:47.800 --> 00:09:50.340
then it doesn't really matter.

00:09:50.340 --> 00:09:52.330
I mean, I always
get a full contrast.

00:09:52.330 --> 00:09:54.590
Even though those frequencies--

00:09:54.590 --> 00:09:58.130
I mean, [INAUDIBLE] plane-- the
frequency of the interference

00:09:58.130 --> 00:09:58.690
is changing.

00:09:58.690 --> 00:10:00.760
But I always get
the full contrast,

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:04.980
but contrast getting smaller if
you have the incoherent source.

00:10:14.020 --> 00:10:20.800
So let me describe
mathematically

00:10:20.800 --> 00:10:22.780
why this happens.

00:10:22.780 --> 00:10:25.600
It doesn't really
matter whether I

00:10:25.600 --> 00:10:28.630
use the Michelson interferometer
or Young's interferometer.

00:10:28.630 --> 00:10:38.750
Basically, interferometer,
we have two waves.

00:10:38.750 --> 00:10:43.610
So a1, e to the pi 1,
and a2, d to the pi 2.

00:10:43.610 --> 00:10:47.450
Basically, we have two waves I
could sample in space or time

00:10:47.450 --> 00:10:47.950
domain.

00:10:47.950 --> 00:10:50.000
But anyway, I'm going
to have two waves

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.880
and just add them together,
and take the magnitude

00:10:52.880 --> 00:10:55.250
square, which is intensity.

00:10:55.250 --> 00:10:59.510
So Michelson
interferometer, this is--

00:10:59.510 --> 00:11:06.090
I mean, these two waves came
from the different-- the path

00:11:06.090 --> 00:11:07.940
length, d1 and d2.

00:11:07.940 --> 00:11:11.270
And Young's interferometer,
basically, they

00:11:11.270 --> 00:11:15.050
came from the two different
pinholes, x1 and x2.

00:11:15.050 --> 00:11:17.750
But anyway, I can always
write the interference

00:11:17.750 --> 00:11:19.940
of two waves like this.

00:11:19.940 --> 00:11:24.990
So wave one and wave
two, it's negative square

00:11:24.990 --> 00:11:30.374
is going to be i0 and 1 plus m
cosine, the phase difference.

00:11:30.374 --> 00:11:32.834
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:32.834 --> 00:11:35.420
SE BAEK OH: We are assuming
monochromatic, yes.

00:11:35.420 --> 00:11:37.050
I mean, you can write--

00:11:37.050 --> 00:11:41.210
[INAUDIBLE] we use
assuming monochromatic

00:11:41.210 --> 00:11:43.040
because we're using
phase notation.

00:11:43.040 --> 00:11:47.510
So we write this
and we write phaser,

00:11:47.510 --> 00:11:51.350
but actually, there is e
to the i or negative i.

00:11:51.350 --> 00:11:55.490
So yeah, we assume
it's monochromatic.

00:11:55.490 --> 00:11:58.100
But even though
it's not chromatic,

00:11:58.100 --> 00:12:01.548
you can always write just
addition of two waves.

00:12:01.548 --> 00:12:02.590
It really doesn't matter.

00:12:08.770 --> 00:12:12.460
So interference is basically
the dc term which is i0.

00:12:12.460 --> 00:12:16.210
So i0 is actually a1
squared plus a2 squared,

00:12:16.210 --> 00:12:20.800
which is intensity of wave
1 and intensity of wave 2.

00:12:20.800 --> 00:12:25.090
So dc term is just
addition of the intensity,

00:12:25.090 --> 00:12:28.400
and we have some
cosine modulation term.

00:12:33.430 --> 00:12:36.890
So this is basically
interference.

00:12:36.890 --> 00:12:43.000
So if we have coherent light,
then we have some dc term,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:47.020
and have a sinusoidal
modulation.

00:12:47.020 --> 00:12:52.660
And as the phase
varies, we're going

00:12:52.660 --> 00:12:55.640
to see the sinusoidal
pattern is changing.

00:12:55.640 --> 00:12:59.740
But remember that this optical
frequency is very fast--

00:12:59.740 --> 00:13:03.850
like tens of
gigahertz [INAUDIBLE]..

00:13:03.850 --> 00:13:05.500
So actually, what we measure--

00:13:05.500 --> 00:13:07.780
I mean, intensity is
time average of this guy.

00:13:07.780 --> 00:13:14.560
So we're going to take the
time average of intensity.

00:13:14.560 --> 00:13:17.680
And if you do the math--

00:13:17.680 --> 00:13:20.580
actually, we have the
dc term and this kind

00:13:20.580 --> 00:13:25.710
of modulation term, which
is time average of cosine

00:13:25.710 --> 00:13:27.780
with a phase difference.

00:13:27.780 --> 00:13:30.380
But remember that if we
have incoherent light,

00:13:30.380 --> 00:13:32.200
this phase difference is random.

00:13:32.200 --> 00:13:36.270
So what is the average of
cosine of random phase?

00:13:39.870 --> 00:13:40.799
[INAUDIBLE]

00:13:49.550 --> 00:13:53.280
What is the average of
cosine or random phase?

00:13:56.440 --> 00:13:56.940
AUDIENCE: Q.

00:13:56.940 --> 00:13:59.370
SE BAEK OH: Yeah, Q.
Cosine is oscillating

00:13:59.370 --> 00:14:02.160
between plus 1 and to minus 1.

00:14:02.160 --> 00:14:06.720
So if you have random phase
and average, then you get 0.

00:14:06.720 --> 00:14:11.100
So if you have incoherent
light, then basically intensity

00:14:11.100 --> 00:14:13.125
is just addition of--

00:14:13.125 --> 00:14:15.210
the intensity of 2
waves, and we don't

00:14:15.210 --> 00:14:17.070
have any interference term.

00:14:17.070 --> 00:14:20.520
So that's the difference between
coherent and incoherent light.

00:14:20.520 --> 00:14:24.030
So coherent light, you always
have a modulation term.

00:14:24.030 --> 00:14:26.950
I mean, it could be 0
depending on phase difference.

00:14:26.950 --> 00:14:32.130
But in [INAUDIBLE],, you always
have just addition of dc term--

00:14:32.130 --> 00:14:33.744
I mean addition of intensity.

00:14:41.590 --> 00:14:44.530
So if it's perfectly
incoherent, then we

00:14:44.530 --> 00:14:46.570
have just addition of intensity.

00:14:46.570 --> 00:14:49.875
And actually, coherent
and incoherent is very--

00:14:49.875 --> 00:14:53.260
actually two opposite
extreme cases.

00:14:53.260 --> 00:14:57.197
So it's just like monochromatic.

00:14:57.197 --> 00:14:58.780
In real case, we are
not going to have

00:14:58.780 --> 00:15:02.080
really monochromatic source.

00:15:02.080 --> 00:15:05.070
Our source is always
finite bandwidth.

00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:06.570
It's not going to
be delta function.

00:15:06.570 --> 00:15:07.760
So it's same thing.

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:11.670
We are not going to have the
perfectly coherent or perfectly

00:15:11.670 --> 00:15:12.250
incoherent.

00:15:12.250 --> 00:15:15.190
Everything is
partially coherent.

00:15:15.190 --> 00:15:19.990
So if you want to deal with
it, then you have to apply

00:15:19.990 --> 00:15:25.720
basically statistics to all
these Fresnel and [INAUDIBLE]----

00:15:25.720 --> 00:15:27.770
I mean, this kind of
[INAUDIBLE] optics.

00:15:27.770 --> 00:15:29.950
So it's called
statistical optics,

00:15:29.950 --> 00:15:32.980
and it's covered in 2.707.

00:15:32.980 --> 00:15:36.230
So if you want to
learn more about it,

00:15:36.230 --> 00:15:39.940
then you can take 2.7 or 1.7.

00:15:39.940 --> 00:15:42.760
But nevertheless, the
coherent and incoherent case

00:15:42.760 --> 00:15:46.990
are enough to describe
many, many phenomena.

00:15:46.990 --> 00:15:53.506
So we are focused on coherent
and incoherent state detection.

00:15:57.350 --> 00:15:58.350
Going a little bit fast.

00:16:02.110 --> 00:16:07.728
So-- oops.

00:16:07.728 --> 00:16:08.228
Sorry.

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:17.620
So since we have two
kinds of coherence-- so

00:16:17.620 --> 00:16:20.310
temporal coherence
and spatial coherence.

00:16:20.310 --> 00:16:24.230
So actually, we have four
different combinations.

00:16:24.230 --> 00:16:26.320
So temporarily and
spatially coherent,

00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:29.030
and temporarily/spatially
incoherent.

00:16:29.030 --> 00:16:33.740
And temporal incoherent,
spatially coherent, temporarily

00:16:33.740 --> 00:16:35.940
coherent, spatially incoherent.

00:16:35.940 --> 00:16:39.040
So the rule of thumb--

00:16:39.040 --> 00:16:42.460
so temporal coherence is
related to the bandwidth

00:16:42.460 --> 00:16:44.590
of your source--

00:16:44.590 --> 00:16:47.300
basically, the color
of your source.

00:16:47.300 --> 00:16:50.930
So if you have one color in
monochromatic, then it's--

00:16:50.930 --> 00:16:51.890
question?

00:16:51.890 --> 00:16:55.240
AUDIENCE: Yeah, where do
diode lasers go in that chart?

00:16:57.750 --> 00:17:00.392
SE BAEK OH: Diode laser
is more like temporally

00:17:00.392 --> 00:17:01.350
and spatially coherent.

00:17:05.780 --> 00:17:07.520
So yeah, let me just continue.

00:17:07.520 --> 00:17:10.500
So temporal coherence
is related to color.

00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:13.760
So if you have laser, like
single-color monochromatic,

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:15.869
then it's more like coherent.

00:17:15.869 --> 00:17:18.710
But if you have white light,
like this fluorescent lamp

00:17:18.710 --> 00:17:21.800
or halogen lamp,
then it's broadband,

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:24.349
so it's temporally incoherent.

00:17:24.349 --> 00:17:28.520
And spatial coherence is
related to actually the size

00:17:28.520 --> 00:17:30.820
of the source and the distance.

00:17:30.820 --> 00:17:32.945
So everything coming
from the point source

00:17:32.945 --> 00:17:36.890
is spatially coherent
because they're basically

00:17:36.890 --> 00:17:38.720
coming from the same point.

00:17:38.720 --> 00:17:41.550
But if your source
is extended like--

00:17:41.550 --> 00:17:43.820
or you have the
filament in a bulb,

00:17:43.820 --> 00:17:46.040
or this kind of
fluorescent light,

00:17:46.040 --> 00:17:49.190
then it's spatially incoherent.

00:17:49.190 --> 00:17:53.240
So the monochromatic
laser source,

00:17:53.240 --> 00:17:59.630
laser is very monochromatic,
and the output is very small.

00:17:59.630 --> 00:18:02.870
So laser is typically very
temporarily and spatially

00:18:02.870 --> 00:18:05.930
incoherent, and that's
why people use it

00:18:05.930 --> 00:18:08.360
in interferometry.

00:18:08.360 --> 00:18:11.060
And white light source--

00:18:11.060 --> 00:18:13.620
and if you are nearby
the white light source,

00:18:13.620 --> 00:18:19.610
then it's more like temporally
and spatially incoherent.

00:18:19.610 --> 00:18:23.110
And actually, these two are
a little bit interesting.

00:18:23.110 --> 00:18:26.130
So temporally incoherent
or spatially coherent.

00:18:26.130 --> 00:18:30.020
So if you put a small pinhole
in front of the white light,

00:18:30.020 --> 00:18:33.530
then it's temporally incoherent
because it's broadband,

00:18:33.530 --> 00:18:36.500
but it's coming from a pinhole,
so it's spatially coherent.

00:18:36.500 --> 00:18:42.080
At the same reason, the sunlight
is very spatially coherent,

00:18:42.080 --> 00:18:43.730
but temporally incoherent.

00:18:43.730 --> 00:18:47.150
But the sun is very huge, but
also the distance is very huge.

00:18:47.150 --> 00:18:51.240
So if you see the
sun, then it looks--

00:18:51.240 --> 00:18:53.000
sunlight is coming
from point source,

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:57.854
so that's why it's
spatially coherent.

00:18:57.854 --> 00:19:00.500
And yeah, the light from--

