00:24:36.500 --> 00:24:39.950
to the laser beam where
we can say it destroyed

00:24:39.950 --> 00:24:42.120
the correlation of the related.

00:24:42.120 --> 00:24:45.770
So it's monochromatic,
so it temporally coheres.

00:24:45.770 --> 00:24:48.270
But in space domain,
it is a random phase,

00:24:48.270 --> 00:24:52.040
so you can have the
spatially incoherent light.

00:24:56.430 --> 00:24:59.750
So these are a list of
optical instruments using

00:24:59.750 --> 00:25:02.416
spatial coherence on imaging.

00:25:02.416 --> 00:25:05.420
The Michelson stellar
interferometer and the radio

00:25:05.420 --> 00:25:09.920
telescope, they are basically
measuring spatial coherence

00:25:09.920 --> 00:25:14.260
of the light coming from a
distant star, or sun, or--

00:25:14.260 --> 00:25:16.340
yeah, they're basically
for astronomy.

00:25:16.340 --> 00:25:18.845
So they can measure,
for example,

00:25:18.845 --> 00:25:22.860
the diameter of a distant star.

00:25:22.860 --> 00:25:24.330
Remember, the
spatial coherence is

00:25:24.330 --> 00:25:26.410
related to the source
size and the distance.

00:25:26.410 --> 00:25:29.080
So if you properly measure
spatial coherence--

00:25:29.080 --> 00:25:31.290
actually, the envelope
of the spatial coherence,

00:25:31.290 --> 00:25:33.450
then you can estimate
the diameter of the star.

00:25:37.072 --> 00:25:39.030
I believe Michelson got
a Nobel Prize for this.

00:25:42.694 --> 00:25:46.220
And optical coherence
tomography is actually

00:25:46.220 --> 00:25:48.310
utilizing temporal incoherence.

00:25:48.310 --> 00:25:51.210
So as I just described, even
though you have white light,

00:25:51.210 --> 00:25:54.200
if you properly match the
optical path difference,

00:25:54.200 --> 00:25:58.440
then you can get interference
within a very small range.

00:25:58.440 --> 00:26:02.840
So let's say you have
multiple layers like tissue,

00:26:02.840 --> 00:26:05.120
and you construct the
Michelson interferometer

00:26:05.120 --> 00:26:08.370
with the white light, and as
you move the other mirror,

00:26:08.370 --> 00:26:10.490
then if the optical
path difference matches,

00:26:10.490 --> 00:26:11.870
then you get interference.

00:26:11.870 --> 00:26:14.120
But if you slightly
off that point,

00:26:14.120 --> 00:26:16.130
then you don't get
the interference.

00:26:16.130 --> 00:26:19.550
So if you plot the interference
versus the distance

00:26:19.550 --> 00:26:22.550
of the mirror, then you
can see kind of the peak

00:26:22.550 --> 00:26:30.440
whenever you have the right
position at each layer.

00:26:30.440 --> 00:26:35.220
So you can kind of do
the optical sectioning.

00:26:35.220 --> 00:26:39.210
And in the lithography
replication technique,

00:26:39.210 --> 00:26:42.470
people use some
spatial coherence

00:26:42.470 --> 00:26:49.640
to basically make
some nice pattern.

00:26:49.640 --> 00:26:52.460
Because as we described
spatial coherence

00:26:52.460 --> 00:26:57.110
is essentially affecting
this resolution

00:26:57.110 --> 00:27:00.340
and the contrast of your image.

00:27:00.340 --> 00:27:14.240
So there are these
kind of things

00:27:14.240 --> 00:27:16.720
Even though we deal with
the spatially coherent

00:27:16.720 --> 00:27:20.200
with the first system, so what
if we change the illumination

00:27:20.200 --> 00:27:24.450
to a spatially incoherent
or temporally incoherent?

00:27:24.450 --> 00:27:30.100
And obviously, my image
will be different depending

00:27:30.100 --> 00:27:33.055
on the coherent state.

00:27:33.055 --> 00:27:38.880
Actually, that's the bottom
line of today's lecture.

00:27:38.880 --> 00:27:42.100
So first, if we have the
temporal incoherent--

00:27:42.100 --> 00:27:44.630
basically, if you have
the broadband for many,

00:27:44.630 --> 00:27:45.730
many colors--

00:27:45.730 --> 00:27:48.880
then the chromatic aberration
is typical evidence

00:27:48.880 --> 00:27:53.410
that I have temporal
incoherent source.

00:27:53.410 --> 00:27:58.420
Then how to deal with it if
you have many, many colors?

00:27:58.420 --> 00:28:00.010
That's pretty straightforward.

00:28:00.010 --> 00:28:03.940
So you can define point spread
function, or ATF, or out--

00:28:03.940 --> 00:28:05.770
or whatever it is.

00:28:05.770 --> 00:28:08.720
You can define that thing
for each wavelength.

00:28:08.720 --> 00:28:11.500
So for example, if I can
define point spread function

00:28:11.500 --> 00:28:13.750
for red wavelength, I can
define point spread function

00:28:13.750 --> 00:28:15.200
for blue wavelengths.

00:28:15.200 --> 00:28:16.000
So it's just--

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:19.840
I can do with a
straightforward equation.

00:28:19.840 --> 00:28:23.010
And spatial coherence
is a little bit--

00:28:23.010 --> 00:28:25.090
and you need to be careful.

00:28:25.090 --> 00:28:28.720
So the bottom-- actually,
this is the take-home message

00:28:28.720 --> 00:28:30.430
of the lecture.

00:28:30.430 --> 00:28:32.680
If the illumination
is spatially coherent,

00:28:32.680 --> 00:28:37.950
then input field is
conversion of the-- actually,

00:28:37.950 --> 00:28:43.090
output field is a
convolution of input field

00:28:43.090 --> 00:28:48.130
with a coherent point spread
function, as we all know.

00:28:48.130 --> 00:28:50.710
But if the illumination
is spatially incoherent,

00:28:50.710 --> 00:28:54.280
then output intensity,
not the output field.

00:28:54.280 --> 00:28:57.160
So output intensity
is a convolution

00:28:57.160 --> 00:29:00.950
of the input intensity with
the incoherent point spread

00:29:00.950 --> 00:29:01.450
function.

00:29:05.170 --> 00:29:12.450
So that's the-- which means
if you have spatial coherent

00:29:12.450 --> 00:29:13.675
illumination, then--

00:29:13.675 --> 00:29:15.270
fields are linear systems.

00:29:15.270 --> 00:29:17.710
You can do the
convolution in field.

00:29:17.710 --> 00:29:20.530
But if the illumination
is incoherent,

00:29:20.530 --> 00:29:22.730
then intensity is
a linear system,

00:29:22.730 --> 00:29:27.640
so you can deal with the
intensity with the convolution.

00:29:27.640 --> 00:29:29.140
So rest of the
lecture, we are going

00:29:29.140 --> 00:29:33.200
to deal with the spatial
incoherent illumination.

00:29:33.200 --> 00:29:37.060
So how we can define point
spread function, and transfer

00:29:37.060 --> 00:29:38.260
function, and et cetera.

00:29:46.760 --> 00:29:51.720
So first, let's review what
we have learned so far.

00:29:51.720 --> 00:29:55.040
So we have fourth
